    en: `I need to have a serious conversation about my cat, whose name is Chairman Meow. Yes, I named him that. No, I do not regret it. What I do regret is the day I brought him home from the shelter, because from that moment on, he has run my entire life with the iron paw of a tiny furry dictator.

It started small. He wanted to be fed at exactly six in the morning. Not six-oh-five. Not five fifty-five. Six. If I was even one minute late, he would sit on my chest and stare at me with those enormous yellow eyes until I woke up in a cold sweat, convinced I was being watched by a demon. Which, technically, I was.

Then he claimed the best spot on the couch. Then the best spot on the bed. Then the entire bed. I now sleep on approximately eleven percent of my own mattress, curled into a shape that my chiropractor says should not be possible for a human spine. Chairman Meow sleeps in the exact center, stretched out like a starfish, purring like a small engine. He has no concerns. He has never had a concern in his life.

The real power move came when he decided that my laptop was his personal heated seat. I work from home three days a week, and without fail, the moment I open my computer, he materializes from thin air and sits directly on the keyboard. I have sent emails to my boss that read things like "jjjjjjjjkkkkkkffffff meow" and "the quarterly report is attached, also my cat says hhhhhhhhhh." My boss thinks I am losing my mind. She might be right.

How much wood would a woodchuck chuck if a woodchuck could chuck wood? I do not know, but I can tell you exactly how much fur a house cat can shed if a house cat decides to shed fur. The answer is an impossible amount. I find cat hair in places that defy the laws of physics. Inside sealed containers. On clothes I have never worn. Once I found a cat hair in a brand new jar of peanut butter that I opened for the first time. He was not even in the room. I think he has mastered quantum mechanics.

Chairman Meow also has opinions about my social life. Whenever someone comes to visit, he performs what I call "the inspection." He walks slowly around the guest, sniffing their shoes, their bag, their hands. If he approves, he will allow them to sit down. If he does not approve, he knocks something off a table while making direct eye contact. It is his way of saying "you may leave now." Most of my friends are terrified of him. The brave ones bring him treats as an offering, like he is some kind of ancient temple cat demanding tribute.

Red lorry, yellow lorry, red lorry, yellow lorry. That is what it sounds like when Chairman Meow chases his toy car across the hardwood floor at three in the morning. Back and forth, back and forth, crash into the wall, back and forth again. I bought him that toy thinking it would tire him out during the day. Instead, he saves all his energy for nighttime demolition derbies.

Despite all of this, I love the little monster. When he curls up on my lap and purrs, when he headbutts my hand demanding pets, when he brings me a sock from the laundry like it is a precious gift, I forget about the sleep deprivation and the cat hair in my food and the emails full of keyboard gibberish. He chose me at the shelter. He walked up to the glass, meowed once, and that was it. I was his human now. And honestly, I would not have it any other way. Even if I do only get eleven percent of the bed.`,
